1
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
*

2
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Who's that?

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Is it you, Edmund?

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Yes.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Ow.

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Turn out that light before you come in.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,000
I'm glad you've come, lad.

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I've been damn lonely.

9
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,000
You're a fine one.

10
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:37,000
You run away and leave me to sit alone here all

11
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:39,000
night, when you know--

12
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
I told you to turn out that light.

13
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:44,000
We're not giving a ball.

14
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
There's no reason to have the house ablaze with electricity

15
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,000
this time of night, burning up money.

16
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Ablaze with electricity?

17
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:51,000
It's one bulb.

18
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Hell, everyone leaves a light on in the hall

19
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:56,000
til they go to bed.

20
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Ow, I damn near busted my knee on that hatstand.

21
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
The light from here shows in the hall.

22
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,000
You'd see your way well enough if you were sober.

23
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:07,000
If I was sober.

24
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Oh, I like that.

25
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:09,000
I don't give a damn what other people do.

26
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:12,000
If they want to be wasteful fools for the sake of show,

27
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:13,000
let them be.

28
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:14,000
It's one bulb.

29
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Christ, don't be such a cheapskate.

30
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,000
I've proved by figures--

31
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:19,000
if you left the light bulb on all night, it wouldn't be as

32
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:20,000
much as one drink.

33
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,000
To hell with your figures.

34
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
The proof is in the bills I have to pay.

35
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Yes, facts don't mean a thing, do they?

36
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:30,000
What you want to believe, that's the only truth.

37
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000


38
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Shakespeare was an Irish Catholic, for example.

39
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
So he was.

40
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,000
The proof is in his plays.

41
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Well, he wasn't.

42
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
There's no proof of it in his plays, except to you.

43
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
The Duke of Wellington is another good Irish Catholic.

44
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:51,000
I never said he was a good one.

45
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Look, I'm not going to argue with you.

46
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:55,000
I told you to turn out that light in the hall.

47
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Yeah, I hear you.

48
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:59,000
As far as I'm concerned, it stays on.

49
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,000
None of your damned insolence.

50
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Are you going to obey me or not?

51
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:04,000
Nah, you want to be a crazy miser?

52
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:05,000
You put it out yourself.

53
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,000
You listen to me.

54
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,000
I've put up with a lot from you because of the mad things

55
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:08,000
you've done at times.

56
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:09,000
I thought you weren't quite right in the head.

57
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
I've excused you and never raised a hand to you, but

58
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
there's a straw that breaks the camel's back.

59
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Now you'll obey me and put out that light or, big as you are,

60
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
I'll give you a thrashing and it'll teach--

61
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:25,000


62
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Forgive me, lad.

63
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
I forgot.

64
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:33,000
You shouldn't goad me into losing my temper.

65
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Ah, forget it, Papa.

66
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:38,000
I apologize too.

67
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:43,000
I had no right being nasty about nothing.

68
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
I am a bit soused, I guess.

69
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000


70
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,000
I'll put out the damn light.

71
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,000
No, stay where you are.

72
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
Let it burn.

73
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
We'll have them all on and let them burn.

74
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:01,000
To hell with it.

75
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
The poor house is the end of the road.

76
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,000
And it might as well be sooner than later.

77
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000


78
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
That's a grand curtain.

79
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:18,000
Oh, you're a wonder, Papa.

80
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:19,000
That's right.

81
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Laugh at the old fool, the poor old ham But the final

82
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
curtain will be in the poor house, just the same and

83
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
that's not comedy.

84
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Oh well, let's not argue.

85
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,000
You got brains in that head of yours, though you do your best

86
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:34,000
to deny them.

87
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
You'll live to learn the value of a dollar.

88
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
You're not like your damn tramp of a brother.

89
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
I've lost all hope he'll ever change.

90
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Where is he, by the way?

91
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:42,000
How would I know?

92
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,000
I thought you went back uptown to meet him?

93
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,000
I walked out to the beach.

94
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,000
I haven't seem him since this afternoon.

95
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,000
If you split the money I gave you with him--

96
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Sure I did.

97
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
He's always staked me when he had anything.

98
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:52,000
Then it doesn't take a soothsayer to tell he's

99
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
probably in the whorehouse.

100
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:54,000
Well, what of it if he is?

101
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Why not?

102
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Why not?

103
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Why not, indeed?

104
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
It's a fit place for him.

105
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
If he's ever had a loftier dream than whores and whiskey,

106
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:01,000
he's never shown it.

107
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
For Pete's sake, Papa, if you're going to start that

108
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:04,000
stuff again, I'll beat it.

109
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:04,000
All right, all right.

110
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:05,000
I'll stop.

111
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
God knows, I don't like the subject either.

112
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:10,000


113
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,000
Will you join me in a drink, lad?

114
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Now you're talking.

115
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000


116
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
I'm wrong to treat you.

117
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
You've had enough already.

118
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Enough is not as good as a feast.

119
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:29,000
Well, it's too much in your condition.

120
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Forget my condition.

121
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000


122
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Here's how.

123
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Drink hearty.

124
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000


125
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
If you walked all the way to the beach, you must be damp

126
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,000
and chilled.

127
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
No, I dropped in at the inn on the way out and back.

128
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
It's not the night I'd pick for a long walk.

129
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
I love the fog.

130
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:55,000
It's what I needed.

131
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:57,000
You should have more since.

132
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:58,000
The hell with sense.

133
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,000
We're all crazy.

134
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:00,000
What do we want with sense?

135
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000


136
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
"They are not long, the weeping and the laughter, love

137
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:10,000
and desire and hate, I think they have no portion in us

138
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
after we pass the gate.

139
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
They are not long, the days of wine and roses.

140
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:23,000
Out of a misty dream our path emerges for a while and closes

141
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:30,000
within a dream." The fog is where I wanted to be.

142
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Halfway down the path, you can't see this house.

143
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Everything looked and sounded unreal.

144
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
Nothing was what it is.

145
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
That's what I wanted, to be alone with myself in another

146
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:50,000
world where the truth is untrue and life

147
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
can hide from itself.

148
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000


149
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Out beyond the harbor where the road runs along the beach.

150
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:06,000
I even lost the feeling I was on land.

151
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:10,000
The fog and the sea, they seemed part of each other.

152
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:17,000
It was like walking on the bottom of the sea as if I'd

153
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:23,000
drowned long ago, as if I was a ghost belonging to the fog,

154
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
and the fog was the ghost of the sea.

155
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000


156
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
Damned peaceful being nothing more than a ghost within a

157
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:45,000
ghost. Stop looking at me as if I'd gone nutty.

158
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
I'm talking sense.

159
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Who wants to see life as it is if they can help it?

160
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:55,000
You've got a poet in you, though it's a damn morbid one.

161
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Devil take your pessimism, I feel low-spirited enough.

162
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Why can't you remember your Shakespeare and forget the

163
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:02,000
third-raters?

164
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:06,000
You'll find whatever you want to say in him and everything

165
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
else that's worth saying.

166
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:16,000
"We are such stuff as dreams are made on and our little

167
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:22,000
life is rounded with a sleep."

168
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,000
That's fine.

169
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:26,000
It's beautiful.

170
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000


171
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:30,000
I wasn't trying to say that.

172
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:34,000


173
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:38,000
We are such stuff as manure is made on.

174
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,000
Oh God, keep such sentiments to yourself--

175
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,000
So let's drink up and forget it.

176
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:41,000
That's more--

177
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:45,000
--I was wrong to give you that drink.

178
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:49,000
Yes, it did pack a whallop, all right, huh?

179
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:54,000
And you too, even if you've never missed a performance.

180
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000


181
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
What's wrong with being drunk?

182
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
It's what we're after, isn't it?

183
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,000
Let's not kid each other, Papa, not tonight.

184
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:10,000
We know what we're trying to forget.

185
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:15,000
But let's not talk about that.

186
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,000
It's no use now.

187
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:21,000


188
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:21,000
No.

189
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:28,000
All we can do is be resigned again.

190
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:31,000
Or be so drunk you can forget.

191
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:33,000
"Be always drunken.

192
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
Nothing else matters, that is the only question.

193
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000


194
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:42,000
If you would not feel the horrible burden of time

195
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,000
weighing on your shoulders, crushing you to the earth, be

196
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
drunken continually.

197
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:51,000


198
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:53,000
Drunken with what?

199
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:01,000
With wine, with poetry or with virtue as you will, but be

200
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,000
drunk."

201
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:06,000
I wouldn't worry about the virtue part of it, I were you.

202
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:08,000
It's morbid nonsense.

203
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:11,000
What little truth there is in it, you'll find nobly said in

204
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
Shakespeare.

205
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:16,000
But you recited it well, lad.

206
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Who wrote it?

207
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
Baudelaire.

208
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Never heard of him.

209
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
Hey, where do you get your taste in authors?

210
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
That damn library of yours--

211
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:31,000
Schopenhauer, Nietzche, Ibsen, atheists, fools and madmen.

212
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:35,000
And your poets, Baudelaire, Oscar Wilde, Whitman, Poe--

213
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
whoremongers and degenerates.

214
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,000
And I've got three good sets of Shakespeare right there.

215
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:43,000
You can't accuse me of not knowing Shakespeare.

216
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000


217
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Didn't I win $5 from you once when you bet me I couldn't

218
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:54,000
learn a leading part of his in a week, as you used to do in

219
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
stock in the old days?

220
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:00,000
I learned Macbeth, recited it, letter perfect, with you

221
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:01,000
giving me the cues.

222
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,000
That's right.

223
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,000
So you did.

224
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,000
It was a terrible ordeal, I remember, hearing

225
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:09,000
you murder the lines.

226
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:11,000
I kept wishing I'd paid over the bet without

227
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:12,000
making you prove it.

228
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:16,000


229
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,000
Do you hear?

230
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,000
She's moving around.

231
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:24,000
I was hoping she'd gone to bed.

232
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:33,000


233
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:36,000
Let's forget it.

234
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
How about another drink?

235
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:44,000


236
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:45,000
When did Mama go to bed?

237
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,000
Right after you left.

238
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:48,000
She wouldn't have any dinner.

239
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000


240
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:54,000
What made you run away?

241
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Nothing.

242
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:56,000
Here's how.

243
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:59,000


244
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Drink hearty.

245
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:05,000


246
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
She's moving around a lot.

247
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000


248
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
I hope to God she doesn't come down.

249
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:15,000
Yes.

250
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:19,000
She'll be nothing more than a ghost haunting the past by

251
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:24,000
this time, back before I was born.

252
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Doesn't she do the same thing to me?

253
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Back before she ever knew me?

254
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
You'd think the only happy days she's ever known in her

255
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:33,000
life were in her father's home or in the convent praying and

256
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:34,000
playing the piano.

257
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,000
As I've told you before, lad, you've got to take her

258
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
memories with a grain of salt.

259
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:43,000
Her wonderful home was ordinary enough and her father

260
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,000
wasn't a great, generous, noble Irish

261
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:47,000
gentleman she makes out.

262
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,000
Oh, he was a nice enough man, good company, good talker.

263
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:52,000
I liked him and he liked me.

264
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
He was prosperous enough too in that wholesale grocery

265
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:58,000
business of his, an able man.

266
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:00,000
But he had his weakness.

267
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:03,000
She condemns my drinking but she forgets his.

268
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:07,000
It's true, he never touched a drop until he was 40.

269
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Well, after that, he made up for lost time.

270
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Well, it finished him quick.

271
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:13,000
That and the consumption.

272
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:25,000


273
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:29,000
We don't seem able to avoid unpleasant topics, do we?

274
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:30,000
No.

275
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:35,000


276
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:39,000
What do you say to a game or two of Casino, lad?

277
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:40,000
All right.

278
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:44,000
We can't lock up and go to bed until Jamie comes home on the

279
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,000
last trolley, which I hope he won't.

280
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:48,000
And anyway, I don't want to go upstairs until she's asleep.

281
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:50,000
Neither do I.

282
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:54,000
Now, as I was saying, you've got to take her tales of the

283
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:55,000
past with a grain of salt.

284
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:59,000
The piano playing and her dream of becoming a concert

285
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:00,000
pianist, that was put into her head by the

286
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,000
nuns flattering her.

287
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:03,000
She was their pet.

288
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:05,000
They loved her for being so devoted.

289
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:06,000
They were innocent women anyway, when it

290
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:07,000
comes to the world.

291
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:08,000
Why don't you deal if we're going to play?

292
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,000
I am.

293
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,000


294
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:17,000
And the idea that she might become a nun, that was the

295
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:25,000
worst. Your mother was one of the prettiest girls

296
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,000
you could ever see.

297
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:29,000
She knew it too.

298
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:32,000
She was a bit of a rogue and a coquette--

299
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:36,000
God bless her-- behind all the shyness and the blushes.

300
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:38,000
She was never meant to renounce the world.

301
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:43,000
She was bursting with health and high spirits

302
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:48,000
and the love of loving.

303
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:50,000
For God's sake, Papa, won't you pick up your hand?

304
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:53,000


305
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Let's see, what do I have here?

306
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:59,000


307
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
Listen.

308
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:05,000


309
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,000
She's coming downstairs.

310
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
We'll play our game, pretend not to notice her.

311
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,000
She'll soon go upstairs again.

312
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:32,000


313
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:34,000
I don't see her.

314
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:38,000
She must have started down and then turned back.

315
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:39,000
Thank God.

316
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:42,000


317
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
Yes, it must be pretty horrible to see her the way

318
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
she must be now.

319
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:52,000
The hardest thing to take is the blank walls she builds

320
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,000
around herself.

321
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:58,000
It's more like a bank of fog where she hides and loses

322
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:05,000
herself deliberately, that's the hell of it.

323
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:08,000
You know something in her does it deliberately, get beyond

324
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:14,000
our reach, be rid of us, forget we're alive.

325
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:17,000
It's almost as if-- in spite of loving us--

326
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:18,000
she hated us.

327
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Now, now, now, lad.

328
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:21,000
That's not her.

329
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:22,000
It's that damned poison.

330
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:25,000
Well, she takes it to get that effect.

331
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:29,000
At least I know she did this time.

332
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,000
It's my play, isn't it?

333
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Here.

334
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:36,000
She's been terribly frightened about your illness.

335
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:39,000
Don't be too hard on her, lad.

336
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
Remember, she's not responsible.

337
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,000
Once that poison--

338
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:45,000
I know damned well she's not to blame.

339
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:48,000
You are.

340
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:51,000
If you spent money on a decent doctor when she was so sick

341
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:53,000
after I was born, she'd never have known morphine existed.

342
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:57,000
Instead, you put her in the hands of a hotel quack,

343
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:01,000
wouldn't admit his ignorance, took the easy way out, not

344
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:07,000
giving a damn what happened to her afterwards, and all

345
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:09,000
because his fee was cheap.

346
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:09,000
Be quiet.

347
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:11,000
How dare you talk about something you

348
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
know nothing about?

349
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
You've got to try to see it from my side too, lad.

350
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
How did I know he was that kind of a doctor?

351
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:21,000
He had a good reputation.

