00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,000
thrown money over the bar to buy drinks for everyone on the

546
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:43,000
house, loaned money to sponges I knew would never pay it

547
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:45,000
back-- of course that was in bar rooms when

548
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:48,000
I was full of whiskey.

549
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:50,000
But I can't think that way when I'm sober in my home.

550
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:53,000
And it was at home I first learned the value of a dollar

551
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:55,000
and the fear of the poorhouse.

552
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:57,000
And I've never been able to believe in my luck since.

553
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:00,000
I've always feared it would change and everything I had

554
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:03,000
would be taken away from me.

555
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:07,000
The more property you own, the safer you think you are.

556
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:11,000
Now that may not be logical, but it's the

557
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
way I have to feel.

558
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:17,000
Banks fail, your money's gone.

559
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:21,000
Still, you think you can keep land beneath your feet.

560
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:25,000


561
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:28,000
You said you realized what I was up against as a boy-- the

562
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:29,000
hell you do.

563
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:31,000
How could you?

564
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:35,000
You had everything, nurses, schools, college--

565
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:38,000
though you didn't stay there.

566
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,000
You've had food and clothing.

567
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:45,000


568
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:48,000
When I was 10 years old, my father deserted my mother and

569
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:50,000
went back to Ireland to die, which he did soon enough.

570
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:54,000
I hope to God he's roasting in hell.

571
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:58,000
My mother was left a stranger in a strange land with four

572
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:00,000
small children--

573
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:04,000
myself, a sister a little older and two younger than me.

574
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:06,000
My two older brothers had moved to other parts.

575
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:07,000
They couldn't help.

576
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:11,000
They were hard put to it to keep themselves alive.

577
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:14,000
There were no damned romance in our poverty.

578
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:17,000
Twice we were evicted from a miserable

579
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:20,000
hovel we called home.

580
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:22,000
My mother's few sticks of furniture thrown out into the

581
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:24,000
streets and my mother's and sister's crying.

582
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:27,000


583
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:29,000
I cried too.

584
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:31,000


585
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:34,000
Oh, I tried hard not to because I was the man of the

586
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:38,000
family at 10 years old.

587
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:41,000
There was no more school for me.

588
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
I worked 12 hours a day in a machine shop learning how to

589
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:49,000
make files-- a dirty barn of a place where the rain dripped

590
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,000
through the roof, where you roasted in summer, where

591
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:55,000
there's no stoves so that in winter your hands got numb

592
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:59,000
with cold, where the only light came through two small,

593
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:01,000
filthy windows so that on grey days I sat bent over with my

594
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:06,000
eyes almost touching the files in order to see.

595
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,000
And you talk of work.

596
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000


597
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
And what do you think I got for that?

598
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:15,000


599
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,000
$0.50 a week.

600
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
That's the truth.

601
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:23,000
$0.50 a week.

602
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:29,000
And my poor mother washed and scrubbed for the Yanks by day.

603
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:33,000
My older sister sewed and my two youngers stayed at home to

604
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:37,000
keep the house.

605
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:41,000
We never had clothes enough to wear or enough food to eat.

606
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:45,000
Well, I remember one Thanksgiving--

607
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:49,000
or maybe it was Christmas--

608
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:56,000
a Yank in whose house my mother had been scrubbing gave

609
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:02,000
her a dollar extra for her present.

610
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:07,000
And on the way home she spent it all on food.

611
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:15,000
And I can remember her hugging and kissing us and saying with

612
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:26,000
tears of joy running down her tired face, glory be to God.

613
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:29,000
For once in our lives we'll have enough for each of us.

614
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:38,000


615
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:42,000
She was a fine, brave, sweet woman.

616
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:46,000
There was never a braver or a finer.

617
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,000
She must have been.

618
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:53,000
And her one fear was that she'd get sick and old and

619
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:57,000
have to die in the poor house.

620
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:02,000
And it was in those days I learned to be a miser.

621
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:04,000
A dollar was worth so much then.

622
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:06,000
And once you've learned a lesson, it's

623
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:06,000
hard to unlearn it.

624
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:10,000
You have to look for bargains now.

625
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:13,000
If I took this state farm place for a good bargain, you

626
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:16,000
must forgive me, Edmund.

627
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:18,000
The doctors did say it was a good place.

628
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,000
You must believe that, Edmund.

629
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:24,000
And I swear, I never meant for you to go there if

630
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:24,000
you didn't want to.

631
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:26,000
You can go, choose any place you like.

632
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:27,000
Never mind what it costs.

633
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,000
Any place I can afford.

634
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:29,000
Any place you like--

635
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:36,000


636
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:38,000
within reason.

637
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:51,000


638
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:52,000
It doesn't matter a damn now anyway.

639
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000


640
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:57,000
Let's forget it.

641
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:09,000


642
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:10,000
How about our game?

643
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:15,000


644
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
Whose play is it?

645
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:18,000
I don't know.

646
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:23,000


647
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:29,000
Yeah, maybe life overdid the lesson for me and made a

648
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:32,000
dollar worth too much.

649
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And the time came when that mistake ruined my career as a

650
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:36,000
fine actor.

651
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:40,000


652
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:44,000
I've never admitted this to anyone before, lad, but

653
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:49,000
tonight I'm so heartsick, I feel at the end of everything.

654
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:52,000
And what's the use of fake pride and pretense.

655
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:55,000


656
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:59,000
That God damn play I bought for a song--

657
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:03,000
and made such a success in, such a great money success--

658
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,000
it ruined me with its promise of an easy fortune.

659
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:10,000
And by the time I woke up to the fact that I'd become a

660
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:12,000
slave to the damn thing and did try other

661
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:15,000
plays, it was too late.

662
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:20,000
They'd identified me with that one part and didn't want to

663
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:21,000
see me in anything else.

664
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:24,000


665
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And they were right.

666
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:31,000
I'd lost the great talent I had through years of easy

667
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:31,000
repetition--

668
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:35,000
never learning a new part, never really working hard.

669
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:39,000
$35,000 to $40,000 net profit a season like snapping your

670
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,000
fingers, the temptation was too great.

671
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:50,000
Yep, before I bought the damn thing, I was considered to be

672
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:56,000
one of the three or four young actors with the greatest

673
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:58,000
artistic promise in America.

674
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:00,000


675
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:05,000
I'd worked like hell, left a good job in the machine shop

676
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:08,000
to take super's parts because I loved the theater.

677
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:12,000
I was wild with ambition, read all the plays ever written,

678
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:15,000
studied Shakespeare as you'd study the bible, educated

679
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:18,000
myself, got rid of an Irish brogue you could

680
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:20,000
have cut with a knife.

681
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:24,000
And I loved Shakespeare.

682
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:28,000
I would have acted in any of his plays for nothing, just

683
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:33,000
for the joy of being alive in his great poetry.

684
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:36,000
And I acted well in them too.

685
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:39,000
I felt inspired by him.

686
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:41,000
I could have been a great Shakespearean

687
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:43,000
actor if I'd kept on.

688
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:46,000
I know that.

689
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:58,000
In 1874, when Edwin Booth came to the theater in Chicago

690
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:03,000
where I was leading man, I played Brutus to his Cassius

691
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:05,000
one night, Cassius to his Brutus the next, Othello to

692
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:07,000
his Iago and so on.

693
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:11,000


694
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:15,000
The first night I played Othello, he said to the

695
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:25,000
manager, that young man is playing Othello

696
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:28,000
better than I ever did.

697
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:38,000


698
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:43,000
That from Booth, the greatest actor of

699
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:45,000
his day, or any other.

700
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:50,000


701
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
And it was true.

702
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:58,000
And I was only 27 years old.

703
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:01,000
And when I look back on it now, that was the

704
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:02,000
high spot of my career.

705
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,000
I had life where I wanted it.

706
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:06,000
And for a time after, went on upward with ambition.

707
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:08,000
I married your mother.

708
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:11,000
Ask her what I was like in those days.

709
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:15,000
Her love was an added incentive to my ambition.

710
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:21,000
Then, a few years later my good bad luck made me find the

711
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:21,000
big moneymaker.

712
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:24,000
Well, it wasn't that at first. It was just a great, romantic

713
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:26,000
part I knew I could play better than anyone.

714
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:31,000
But it was a great box office success from the start.

715
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:33,000
And then life had me where it wanted me.

716
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:37,000


717
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:43,000
$35,000 to $40,000 net profit a season, a fortune in those

718
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:47,000
days, even in these.

719
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:55,000


720
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:57,000
What the hell was it--

721
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:00,000
I wonder--

722
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:02,000
I wanted to buy that was worth--

723
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:09,000


724
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:13,000
ah well, it's a late day for regrets.

725
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:20,000


726
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:22,000
It's my play, isn't it?

727
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:27,000


728
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:31,000
I'm glad you told me this, Papa.

729
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:36,000
I know you a lot better now.

730
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:39,000
Maybe I shouldn't have told you.

731
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:43,000
Maybe you'll only feel more contempt for me.

732
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:45,000
And it's a poor way to convince you of

733
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:46,000
the value of a dollar.

734
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:51,000


735
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:54,000
The glare from those extra lights hurts my eyes.

736
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:56,000
You don't mind if I turn them out, do you?

737
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:58,000
We don't need them and there's no point in making the

738
00:35:58,000 --> 00:35:59,000
electric company rich.

739
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:01,000
No.

740
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,000


741
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:04,000
Sure not.

742
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Turn them out.

743
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:11,000
No, I don't know what the hell it was I wanted to buy.

744
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:15,000


745
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:21,000
By my solemn oath, Edmund, I'd gladly have no home but the

746
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:25,000
poorhouse in my old age if I could look back now on having

747
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:26,000
been the fine artist I might have been.

748
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:31,000


749
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:33,000
What the devil are you laughing at?

750
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:34,000
Not at you, Papa.

751
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:37,000
At life, it's so damn crazy.

752
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:38,000
Nothing wrong with life.

753
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:40,000
It's we.

754
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:44,000
"The fault, dear Brutus, is not in our stars but in

755
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:49,000
ourselves, that we are underlings." You know the

756
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:52,000
praise Edwin Booth gave my Othello?

757
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:57,000
I made the manager put down his exact words in writing,

758
00:36:57,000 --> 00:36:59,000
kept it in my wallet for years.

759
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:02,000
I took it out every once in a while to read it until finally

760
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:07,000
it made me feel so bad I couldn't face it anymore.

761
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:10,000


762
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:12,000
Where is it now, I wonder?

763
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:15,000
It's somewhere in this house because I remember I put it

764
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:18,000
away carefully.

765
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:21,000
It might be in an old trunk in the attic along with Mama's

766
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:22,000
wedding dress.

767
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:24,000


768
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:27,000
For Pete's sake, if we're going to play cards, let's

769
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:28,000
play cards.

770
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:30,000


771
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:32,000
She's still moving around.

772
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:35,000
God knows when she's going to go to sleep.

773
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:36,000
For Christ's sake, Papa, just forget it.

774
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:44,000


775
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:49,000
You just told me some high spots in your memories.

776
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:50,000
Want to hear mine?

777
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:54,000


778
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:55,000
They're all connected with the sea.

779
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:03,000


780
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:06,000
Here's one.

781
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:08,000
When I was on the square head--

782
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:11,000
square rigger--

783
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:15,000
bound for Buenos Aires, full moon in the Trades, the old

784
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:23,000
hooker driving 14 knots, I lay on the bowsprit facing astern

785
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:29,000
with the water foaming into spume under me and the mast--

786
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:31,000
with every sail-- white in the moonlight,

787
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:32,000
towering high above me.

788
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:34,000


789
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:37,000
And I became drunk with the beauty and

790
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:38,000
singing rhythm of it.

791
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:41,000


792
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:45,000
And for a moment I lost myself.

793
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:49,000


794
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:52,000
I actually lost my life.

795
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:54,000
I was set free.

796
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:58,000
I dissolved in the sea.

797
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:02,000
I became white sails and flying spray.

798
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:05,000
I became beauty and rhythm.

799
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:09,000
I became the moonlight and the ship and the

800
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:12,000
high, dim starred skies.

801
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:14,000
I belonged--

802
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:19,000
without past or future-- within peace and unity and a

803
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:26,000
wild joy, within something greater than my own life or

804
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:29,000
the life of man--

805
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:40,000
to life itself, to God, if you want to put it that way.

806
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:44,000
And several other times in my life, when I've been swimming

807
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:50,000
far out or lying alone on a beach, I've had the same

808
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:51,000
experience.

809
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:59,000
I became the sun, hot sand, green seaweed anchored to a

810
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:01,000
rock, swaying in the tide--

811
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:04,000


812
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:12,000
like a saint's vision of beatitude, like the veil of

813
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:19,000
things as they seem drawn back by an unseen hand and for a

814
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:22,000
second you see.

815
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:26,000
And seeing the secret, you are the secret.

